## Borough and County in New York, United States

### Queens

**Queens County, New York**

**[Borough](/Boroughs_of_New_York_City)** and **[county](/List_of_counties_in_New_York)**

Queens. The largest by area of the [five boroughs](/Boroughs_of_New_York_City) that constitute [New York City](/New_York_City). It’s also, inconveniently, coextensive with Queens County, a fact that seems to matter more to cartographers than to the people actually living there. Nestled near the western edge of [Long Island](/Long_Island), it’s a place that’s both intimately connected and frustratingly isolated. It’s bordered by [Brooklyn](/Brooklyn) to its south and west, and then, predictably, by [Nassau County](/Nassau_County,_New_York) to its east. Maritime borders? Of course. It shares those with [Manhattan](/Manhattan), [The Bronx](/The_Bronx), and [Staten Island](/Staten_Island), and even stretches its watery reach to [New Jersey](/New_Jersey).

They say Queens is the most linguistically diverse place on Earth. I suppose that’s one way of putting it. It’s also one of the most ethnically diverse. So, a lot of languages, a lot of faces, a lot of noise. Not exactly my ideal symphony.

As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), the population clocked in at a considerable 2,405,464 souls. That makes it the second most populous county in [New York State](/New_York_(state)), trailing only Kings County, which is, of course, [Brooklyn](/Brooklyn). If Queens were its own city, a hypothetical thought that’s unlikely to ever materialize, it would rank as the fourth most populous in the [U.S.](/United_States), trailing only the rest of [New York City](/New_York_City), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), and [Chicago](/Chicago). Its population density is middling, fourth in the borough hierarchy, fourth in the county pecking order. And the foreign-born population? A staggering 47%. Makes sense. People are always looking for a place to land, I suppose.

Originally, in 1683, Queens County was a bit… bigger. It encompassed the area that is now [Nassau County](/Nassau_County,_New_York). It was one of the original twelve counties of the [Province of New York](/Province_of_New_York). And the name? Supposedly after [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza), a Portuguese royal princess and English Queen. From 1683 to 1899, the county’s boundaries stretched further east. Then came the consolidation of [New York City](/New_York_City) in 1898, which folded in [Long Island City](/Long_Island_City), [Newtown](/Elmhurst,_Queens), [Flushing](/Flushing,_Queens), [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens), and the western part of [Hempstead](/Hempstead,_New_York). Most of these places are still considered neighborhoods, clinging to their former identities within the larger sprawl.

Economically, Queens is a bit of a chameleon. It boasts the most diversified economy of all the boroughs. It’s home to both of [New York City's](/New_York_City) major airports: [John F. Kennedy International Airport](/John_F._Kennedy_International_Airport) and [LaGuardia Airport](/LaGuardia_Airport). Landmarks? Plenty. [Flushing Meadows–Corona Park](/Flushing_Meadows%E2%80%93Corona_Park), [Citi Field](/Citi_Field) (home of the [New York Mets](/New_York_Mets)), the [USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center](/USTA_Billie_Jean_King_National_Tennis_Center) for the [U.S. Open](/U.S._Open_(Tennis)), [Kaufman Astoria Studios](/Kaufman_Astoria_Studios), [Silvercup Studios](/Silvercup_Studios), and the [Aqueduct Racetrack](/Aqueduct_Racetrack). [Flushing](/Flushing,_Queens) is currently in a state of rapid transformation, thanks to investments from Chinese entities. [Long Island City](/Long_Island_City) is following suit, its proximity to [Manhattan](/Manhattan) across the [East River](/East_River) fueling its gentrification.

### History

#### Colonial and Post-Colonial History

The first European footprints in this region belonged to the [Dutch](/Dutch_colonization_of_the_Americas), who established the colony of [New Netherland](/New_Netherland). Settlements began in 1635, followed by a short-lived attempt at [Maspeth](/Maspeth,_Queens) in 1642, and then the founding of Vlissingen, now [Flushing](/Flushing,_Queens), in 1645. Newtown, now [Elmhurst](/Elmhurst,_Queens), appeared in 1652, and [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens) in 1655. Oddly enough, these towns, though under Dutch jurisdiction, were largely populated by English settlers migrating from [New England](/New_England) via eastern [Long Island](/Long_Island) ([Suffolk County](/Suffolk_County,_New_York)). When the English swooped in and claimed the colony in 1664, renaming it New York, this area, along with all of Long Island, became known as [Yorkshire](/Yorkshire_County,_Province_of_New_York).

The [Flushing Remonstrance](/Flushing_Remonstrance), signed by colonists in 1657, is often cited as a precursor to the [United States Constitution](/United_States_Constitution)'s guarantee of [freedom of religion](/Freedom_of_religion) found in the [Bill of Rights](/United_States_Bill_of_Rights). It was a protest against the Dutch authorities’ persecution of [Quakers](/Quakers) within what is now Queens.

