Originally, Queens County included the land that is now [Nassau County](/Nassau_County,_New_York). It was one of the original twelve counties established in New York State on November 1, 1683. The county's name is widely believed to honor [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza), the queen consort of England at the time. She was the daughter of King [John IV of Portugal](/John_IV_of_Portugal). It’s worth noting that [Kings County](/Brooklyn) (named for her husband, Charles II) and [Richmond County](/Staten_Island) (named for his illegitimate son, [Charles Lennox, 1st Duke of Richmond](/Charles_Lennox,_1st_Duke_of_Richmond)) were established concurrently. However, the official declaration naming Catherine as the namesake remains elusive, leaving a sliver of doubt. On October 7, 1691, the counties were redefined. Queens gained [North and South Brother Islands](/North_and_South_Brother_Islands,_New_York_City) and Huletts Island, which we now know as [Rikers Island](/Rikers_Island). Then, on December 3, 1768, Queens acquired further islands in [Long Island Sound](/Long_Island_Sound) that weren't already designated to another county, provided they didn't abut [Westchester County](/Westchester_County) (which is now [Bronx County](/The_Bronx)).

Queens played a rather minor role in the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution), especially when compared to Brooklyn, where the pivotal [Battle of Long Island](/Battle_of_Long_Island) took place. Like the rest of what would become New York City and Long Island, Queens remained under British occupation following the Battle of Long Island in 1776 and stayed that way for most of the [Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War). Under the terms of the [Quartering Act](/Quartering_Act), British soldiers commandeered public inns and vacant buildings belonging to Queens residents for use as [barracks](/Barracks). Despite many residents’ disapproval of this unannounced quartering, they generally supported the British crown. The practice of quartering soldiers in private homes, outside of wartime, was later prohibited by the [Third Amendment to the United States Constitution](/Third_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution). It’s also worth mentioning that [Nathan Hale](/Nathan_Hale), the famous spy, was captured by the British along the shores of [Flushing Bay](/Flushing_Bay) and subsequently [hanged](/Hanging) in [Manhattan](/Manhattan).

From 1683 until 1784, Queens County was divided into five towns: Flushing, [Hempstead](/Town_of_Hempstead,_New_York), [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens), [Newtown](/Elmhurst,_Queens), and [Oyster Bay](/Town_of_Oyster_Bay,_New_York). Then, on April 6, 1784, the Town of [North Hempstead](/Town_of_North_Hempstead,_New_York) was carved out from the northern sections of the Town of Hempstead. The county seat initially resided in Jamaica. However, during the American Revolution, the British dismantled the courthouse to use the materials for barracks. After the war, various buildings in Jamaica served as temporary courthouses and jails until a new building was constructed around 1787, near what was then known as Clowesville, in the area now part of Nassau County.

The [1850 United States census](/1850_United_States_census) marked the first time the population of the three western towns surpassed that of the three eastern towns that would eventually form Nassau County. Concerns about the deteriorating condition and inconvenient location of the old courthouse were mounting, and multiple sites were being considered for a new one.

In 1870, [Long Island City](/Long_Island_City) officially separated from the Town of Newtown, incorporating itself as a city. This new entity comprised the [village of Astoria](/Astoria,_Queens) and some unincorporated areas within Newtown. Around 1874, the county government’s seat was relocated from Mineola to Long Island City.

On March 1, 1860, the eastern boundary between Queens County (and later Nassau County) and [Suffolk County](/Suffolk_County,_New_York) was redefined, though the change itself was not significant. Then, on June 8, 1881, [North Brother Island](/North_Brother_Island,_East_River) was transferred to [New York County](/Manhattan). Later, on May 8, 1884, [Rikers Island](/Rikers_Island) followed suit, also being transferred to New York County.

In 1886, Lloyd's Neck, which was then part of the town of Oyster Bay and had previously been known as Queens Village, was detached from Queens County and annexed to the town of Huntington in Suffolk County. Finally, on April 16, 1964, [South Brother Island](/South_Brother_Island,_East_River) was ceded to Bronx County.

#### Incorporation as Borough

The creation of the New York City borough of Queens was greenlit on May 4, 1897, following a referendum on consolidation held in 1894. The eastern 280 square miles (730 km²) of Queens that would eventually become [Nassau County](/Nassau_County,_New_York) were officially partitioned on January 1, 1899. The Borough of Queens itself was established on January 1, 1898.

The consolidation plan annexed the city of [Long Island City](/Long_Island_City), the towns of [Newtown](/Newtown,_Queens_County,_New_York), [Flushing](/Flushing,_Queens), and [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens), along with a specific western portion of the town of [Hempstead](/Hempstead,_New_York). This annexation effectively dissolved all former municipal governments, including [Long Island City](/Long_Island_City), the county government, all towns, and all villages within the newly formed borough. However, the areas of Queens County not included in this consolidation plan – namely the towns of North Hempstead and Oyster Bay, and the remaining major part of the Town of Hempstead – remained part of Queens County until they were officially separated to form [Nassau County](/Nassau_County,_New_York) on January 1, 1899. At this point, the boundaries of Queens County and the Borough of Queens became identical. Jamaica was reinstated as the county seat, though county offices have since expanded to nearby [Kew Gardens](/Kew_Gardens,_Queens).

In 1899, a land survey conducted by New York City aimed to pinpoint the exact border of Queens between [the Rockaways](/The_Rockaways) and [Lawrence](/Lawrence,_Nassau_County,_New_York). This proved challenging because the border was defined by the "middle of the channel between Rockaway Beach and Shelter Island" (now Long Beach Island), a channel that had silted up by 1899. Surveyors had to rely on historical data and local knowledge, including the testimony of fishermen and oystermen, to determine the channel's original course.

Between 1905 and 1908, the [Long Island Rail Road](/Long_Island_Rail_Road) within Queens underwent electrification. Transportation to and from [Manhattan](/Manhattan) was significantly improved with the completion of the [Queensboro Bridge](/Queensboro_Bridge) in 1909 and the opening of railway tunnels under the [East River](/East_River) in 1910. From 1915 onwards, large sections of Queens became integrated into the [New York City Subway](/New_York_City_Subway) system. The construction of the [Steinway Tunnel](/Steinway_Tunnel) in 1915, carrying the [IRT Flushing Line](/IRT_Flushing_Line) between Queens and Manhattan, coupled with the increasing popularity of the [automobile](/Automobile), led to a dramatic population surge in Queens during the 1920s. The population more than doubled, from 469,042 in 1920 to 1,079,129 in 1930.

Queens later became the site for two major international expositions: the [1939 New York World's Fair](/1939_New_York_World%27s_Fair) and the [1964 New York World's Fair](/1964_New_York_World%27s_Fair). [LaGuardia Airport](/LaGuardia_Airport), established on a site that was previously a seaplane base in northern Queens, opened in 1939 and was named in honor of Mayor [Fiorello La Guardia](/Fiorello_La_Guardia), who championed the development of a modern airport for the city. Idlewild Airport, situated in southern Queens on the grounds of a former golf course, opened in 1948 and was later renamed [John F. Kennedy International Airport](/John_F._Kennedy_International_Airport) in 1963. In a tragic turn of events, [TWA Flight 800](/TWA_Flight_800) departed from JFK on July 17, 1996, only to explode in mid-air off the coast of Long Island, resulting in the deaths of all 230 people aboard the [Boeing 747](/Boeing_747). More recently, on November 12, 2001, [American Airlines Flight 587](/American_Airlines_Flight_587) crashed in [Belle Harbor](/Belle_Harbor,_Queens) shortly after taking off from JFK, killing all 260 on board and five people on the ground. In late October 2012, [Hurricane Sandy](/Hurricane_Sandy) caused extensive damage to [Breezy Point](/Breezy_Point,_Queens), where a massive fire destroyed 126 homes, marking the largest residential fire in the history of the Fire Department of New York (FDNY).

